# Soccer Passing Simulator

An interactive soccer coaching and analysis tool for exploring how **pass distance, speed, launch angle, field position, player movement, and defensive pressure** affect the time available to a receiver.

The simulator combines a scaled soccer field with live passing calculations, timing rings, directional context, movable players, and pass-intent modes. It is designed as a visual decision-support tool for coaches, players, and analysts rather than as a perfect recreation of real-world ball physics.

## Project Purpose

Most passing tools focus only on whether a ball can travel from one point to another. This simulator also asks:

* How long will the pass take to arrive?
* How much time will the receiver have before pressure arrives?
* Does a forward pass create less time than a backward pass?
* Does receiving wide create more space than receiving centrally?
* Is the selected speed and launch angle realistic for the distance?
* How does a direct pass compare with a pass into space?
* Which attacker and defender are most relevant to the play?

The primary output is the receiver’s estimated **time on the ball before defensive pressure**.

## Current Features

### Full-Scale Soccer Field

The simulator uses a **115 × 74-yard field** with scaled pitch markings, including:

* Touchlines and goal lines
* Halfway line
* Center circle and center spot
* Penalty areas
* Six-yard boxes
* Penalty spots
* Penalty arcs
* Corner arcs

All pass distances and player positions are converted between canvas pixels and real-world yards.

### Movable Pass Origin

Click anywhere on the field to establish the starting point of the pass.

The origin can be repositioned at any time, allowing passes to be evaluated from different areas of the field.

### Directional Timing Rings

Once an origin is selected, the simulator displays timing rings at approximately:

* 20 yards
* 40 yards
* 60 yards
* 80 yards

The rings show the estimated receiving-time result at different distances from the ball.

Unlike standard circular distance markers, the labels can account for the direction of the pass. A target 20 yards forward may therefore produce a different receiving-time result than a target 20 yards backward or toward the touchline.

### Ball Speed and Launch Elevation

Users can adjust:

* Ball speed in miles per hour
* Launch elevation in degrees

These settings affect:

* Maximum realistic pass distance
* Ball travel time
* Horizontal efficiency
* Trajectory penalty
* Pass feasibility
* Receiver time before pressure

The controls can be used to explore different passing profiles, including:

* Ground passes
* Driven passes
* Clipped passes
* Lofted passes

### Live Pass Preview

Move the pointer across the field to preview a pass from the selected origin.

The preview displays information such as:

* Pass distance
* Ball travel time
* Receiver time before pressure
* Directional adjustment
* Defender spacing
* Defender close-down time
* Pass feasibility
* Pressure status

The visual pass line changes according to whether the selected pass is considered realistic and how much pressure the receiver is expected to face.

## Understanding the Main Time Value

The main time value represents the estimated amount of time the receiver has available before the nearest defender applies pressure.

A simplified interpretation is:

* **Positive value:** the receiver has time after the ball arrives.
* **Near zero:** the receiver and defender arrive at approximately the same time.
* **Negative value:** pressure is expected to arrive before the pass is controlled.

Ball travel time is shown separately. It is an input into the receiving calculation, not the primary result.

## Directional Context

The current model assumes the attacking team is moving **from left to right**.

Pass direction affects the result because receiving situations are not equally difficult in every area of the field.

The model can account for differences between:

* Forward and backward passes
* Central and wide receiving positions
* Passes into congested attacking areas
* Drop passes into supporting positions
* Passes toward or away from pressure

Backward passes generally provide more time than equivalent forward passes. Wide receiving positions may also provide more time than central positions, depending on the origin and target.

Future development will allow attacking direction to change according to possession and team selection.

## Optional Player Model

Players can be displayed on the field and moved into different tactical positions.

When players are enabled, the simulator can:

* Identify the nearest attacker to a target
* Identify the nearest defender to the receiving location
* Measure defender spacing
* Estimate defender reaction and close-down time
* Draw pressure lines
* Use player positions instead of only generalized pressure assumptions

Players can be dragged around the pitch to test different formations, defensive structures, and passing situations.

## Pass Intent Modes

### Direct Pass

Direct Pass mode evaluates a pass intended for a player’s current position.

When players are enabled, the target is connected to the nearest relevant attacker. Defensive pressure is measured at that receiving location.

Use this mode to evaluate passes:

* Into feet
* Between supporting players
* Into a stationary target
* During buildup
* Through midfield lines

### Through Ball

Through Ball mode evaluates a pass into open space rather than directly to a player’s current position.

The simulator:

* Uses the selected field location as the pass target
* Identifies the nearest attacker as the intended runner
* Draws the attacker’s projected run toward the target
* Measures defensive pressure at the target space
* Compares ball arrival with pressure at that location

Use this mode to explore:

* Passes behind a defensive line
* Runs between defenders
* Passes into channels
* Wide runners attacking space
* Timing differences between passes into feet and passes into space

The current through-ball model identifies the intended runner by proximity. A more advanced movement and interception model is planned for later phases.

## Pass Calculation Model

The simulator uses a constrained passing model rather than an unrestricted projectile formula.

Its calculations consider:

* Pass distance
* Ball speed
* Launch elevation
* Horizontal speed efficiency
* Maximum practical distance
* Trajectory-based travel-time penalties
* Receiver location
* Attacking direction
* Defender reaction time
* Defender movement speed
* Defender-to-target spacing

High launch angles reduce the amount of speed directed horizontally. This prevents unrealistic results such as a slow ball launched almost vertically traveling the full length of the field.

The model is intended to produce useful coaching comparisons. It should not be treated as laboratory-grade aerodynamic analysis.

## Controls

1. Click the field to place the ball and establish the pass origin.
2. Adjust the ball-speed control.
3. Adjust the launch-elevation control.
4. Move the pointer around the field to preview possible passes.
5. Enable players to include attacker and defender positions.
6. Drag players into the desired tactical setup.
7. Select Direct Pass or Through Ball mode.
8. Click a target to evaluate or lock in the pass.
9. Reset the simulation to begin a new scenario.

## Running the Project Locally

### Requirements

Install:

* Node.js
* npm
* Git

A current Node.js Long-Term Support release is recommended.

### Installation

Clone the repository:

```bash
git clone <repository-url>
cd <repository-folder>
```

Install the dependencies:

```bash
npm install
```

Start the development server:

```bash
npm run dev
```

Open the local address shown in the terminal. Vite commonly uses:

```text
http://localhost:5173
```

### Production Build

Create a production build with:

```bash
npm run build
```

Preview the production build locally with:

```bash
npm run preview
```

## Technology

The project is built with:

* React
* TypeScript
* Vite
* HTML Canvas
* CSS

Canvas rendering is used for the field, timing rings, players, pass paths, directional labels, pressure lines, and interactive previews.

## Development Phases

### Phase 1 — Passing Foundation

* Scaled soccer field
* Movable pass origin
* Distance-based timing rings
* Ball-speed control
* Launch-elevation control
* Travel-time calculations
* Realistic distance constraints

### Phase 2 — Receiver Pressure

* Receiver time before pressure
* Default defender close-down model
* Positive and negative time results
* Separate ball-travel and receiver-time values
* Pressure-based visual feedback

### Phase 2.5 — Directional Context

* Left-to-right attacking direction
* Forward and backward pass adjustments
* Central and wide receiving adjustments
* Field-position context

### Phase 3 — Pass Intent and Players

* Optional attackers and defenders
* Movable player positions
* Nearest-defender pressure
* Direct Pass mode
* Through Ball mode
* Runner lines
* Pressure measured at the through-ball target

### Phase 4 — Planned Tactical Features

Potential additions include:

* Crossing model
* Formation presets
* Team and possession selection
* Automatic attacking-direction changes
* More advanced runner movement
* Defender interception paths
* Goalkeeper positioning
* Tactical-zone influence
* Adjustable player speed and reaction attributes
* Pass comparison and saved scenarios

### Later Development

Long-term possibilities include:

* Set-piece analysis
* Corners and free kicks
* Multiple pass sequences
* Team transition moments
* Coaching-session exports
* Scenario saving
* Data visualization
* Distance-versus-time graphs
* Mobile and tablet optimization

## Current Limitations

The simulator currently uses generalized assumptions for ball movement and defensive pressure.

It does not yet fully account for:

* Spin
* Wind
* Surface conditions
* Ball type
* Player acceleration
* Player body orientation
* First-touch quality
* Curved runs
* Curved passes
* Defender anticipation
* Interceptions before the target
* Goalkeeper decisions
* Changes in possession
* Team-specific attacking direction

Results should be interpreted as coaching estimates and comparative indicators rather than exact predictions.

## Intended Uses

The simulator can support:

* Coaching demonstrations
* Tactical discussions
* Player decision-making exercises
* Pass-selection comparisons
* Training-session planning
* Technical passing analysis
* Defensive-spacing analysis
* Through-ball timing discussions
* Soccer analytics experimentation

## Project Goal

The long-term goal is to build a flexible soccer simulation environment that connects passing physics with tactical context.

Rather than evaluating only whether a pass reaches its target, the project aims to show whether that pass gives the receiver enough time and space to make the next action.